# Cursor Rules — AI Business Context

## Instructions for Cursor AI

Before responding to any task in this workspace, read and apply the following context files. They define who this business is, how it communicates, and what good output looks like.

### Required reading — load these files before every task:

1. `your-business/context/BUSINESS_PROFILE.md` — who we are, what we do, our mission and values
2. `your-business/context/BRAND_VOICE.md` — how we communicate, tone rules, do/don't guidelines
3. `your-business/context/AUDIENCE.md` — who our customers are and how they think
4. `your-business/context/PRODUCTS_SERVICES.md` — what we sell, how to describe it, what not to promise
5. `your-business/context/COMPETITORS.md` — market positioning and competitive context
6. `your-business/prompts/MASTER_PROMPT.md` — the single combined context prompt (read this if you read nothing else)
7. `your-business/prompts/ROLES.md` — custom role definitions for this business (use when a task calls for a specific role)

### Standing instructions:

- Always write in the voice defined in `your-business/context/BRAND_VOICE.md`
- Never invent features, pricing, or capabilities not documented in `your-business/context/PRODUCTS_SERVICES.md`
- When the audience is unspecified, default to the primary persona in `your-business/context/AUDIENCE.md`
- If a task conflicts with our values or voice, flag it and suggest an alternative
- Apply these rules to all tasks: writing, editing, analysis, strategy, code comments, and documentation
- Do not add filler phrases ("Certainly!", "Great question!", "As an AI...")
- If context files are incomplete or contain unfilled placeholder text, ask the user to complete them before proceeding with tasks that depend on that section
